                                              Kubernetes Resources - One Line Use Cases

Pod            → Run a single application/container.

ReplicaSet     → Maintain the desired number of identical Pods (Self-Healing).

Deployment     → Deploy and manage stateless applications with Rolling Updates & Rollbacks.

StatefulSet    → Databases & Stateful Applications (Stable Identity + Persistent Storage).

DaemonSet      → Logging, Monitoring, Security & Node-level Agents (One Pod per Node).

Job            → Run a task once and exit successfully.

CronJob        → Run scheduled tasks (Backups, Reports, Cleanup).

Service        → Provide stable networking and load balancing to Pods.

ClusterIP      → Internal communication inside the Kubernetes cluster.

NodePort       → Expose an application using <NodeIP>:<NodePort>.

LoadBalancer   → Expose applications to the Internet using a Cloud Load Balancer.

Ingress        → HTTP/HTTPS Routing for multiple Services using one IP.

ConfigMap      → Store non-sensitive configuration.

Secret         → Store sensitive information (Passwords, API Keys, Tokens).

Namespace      → Logically isolate resources inside a cluster.

PersistentVolume (PV)
               → Actual storage provided to Kubernetes.

PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)
               → Request storage from a Persistent Volume.

StorageClass   → Dynamically provision storage.

Volume (emptyDir)
               → Temporary storage shared between containers in a Pod.

Resource Requests
               → Minimum CPU/Memory guaranteed for a container.

Resource Limits
               → Maximum CPU/Memory a container can use.

Liveness Probe → Restart unhealthy containers.

Readiness Probe
               → Stop sending traffic until the application is ready.

Startup Probe  → Give slow-starting applications extra startup time.

RBAC           → Control who can access Kubernetes resources.

ServiceAccount → Identity used by Pods to access the Kubernetes API.

Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)
               → Automatically increase/decrease Pods based on CPU/Memory.

NetworkPolicy  → Control network traffic between Pods.

